#: ../../../usage/streams.md:3
msgid "Redirecting standard streams"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/streams.md:5
msgid ""
"Pyodide has three functions {js:func}`pyodide.setStdin`, {js:func}`pyodide."
"setStdout`, and {js:func}`pyodide.setStderr` that change the behavior of "
"reading from {py:data}`~sys.stdin` and writing to {py:data}`~sys.stdout` and "
"{py:data}`~sys.stderr` respectively."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/streams.md:10
msgid "Standard Input"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/streams.md:14
msgid ""
"{js:func}`pyodide.setStdin` sets the standard in handler. There are several "
"different ways to do this depending on the options passed to `setStdin`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/streams.md:17
msgid "Always raise IO Error"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/streams.md:19
msgid "If we pass `{error: true}`, any read from stdin raises an I/O error."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/streams.md:21
msgid ""
"pyodide.setStdin({ error: true });\n"
"pyodide.runPython(`\n"
"    with pytest.raises(OSError, match=\"I/O error\"):\n"
"        input()\n"
"`);\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/streams.md:29 ../../../usage/streams.md:260
msgid "Set the default behavior"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/streams.md:31
msgid ""
"You can set the default behavior by calling `pyodide.setStdin()` with no "
"arguments. In Node the default behavior is to read directly from Node's "
"standard input. In the browser, the default is the same as `pyodide."
"setStdin({ stdin: () => prompt() })`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/streams.md:36
msgid "A stdin handler"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/streams.md:38
msgid ""
"We can pass the options `{stdin, isatty}`. `stdin` should be a zero-argument "
"function which should return one of:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/streams.md:41
msgid ""
"A string which represents a full line of text (it will have a newline "
"appended if it does not already end in one)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/streams.md:43
msgid "An array buffer or Uint8Array containing utf8 encoded characters"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/streams.md:44
msgid "A number between 0 and 255 which indicates one byte of input"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/streams.md:45
msgid "`undefined` or `null` which indicates EOF."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/streams.md:47
msgid ""
"`isatty` is a boolean which indicates whether `sys.stdin.isatty()` should "
"return `true` or `false`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/streams.md:50
msgid "For example, the following class plays back a list of results."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/streams.md:52
msgid ""
"class StdinHandler {\n"
"  constructor(results, options) {\n"
"    this.results = results;\n"
"    this.idx = 0;\n"
"    Object.assign(this, options);\n"
"  }\n"
"\n"
"  stdin() {\n"
"    return this.results[this.idx++];\n"
"  }\n"
"}\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/streams.md:66
msgid "Here it is in use:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/streams.md:68
msgid ""
"pyodide.setStdin(\n"
"  new StdinHandler([\"a\", \"bcd\", \"efg\"]),\n"
");\n"
"pyodide.runPython(`\n"
"    assert input() == \"a\"\n"
"    assert input() == \"bcd\"\n"
"    assert input() == \"efg\"\n"
"    # after this, further attempts to read from stdin will return undefined "
"which\n"
"    # indicates end of file\n"
"    with pytest.raises(EOFError, match=\"EOF when reading a line\"):\n"
"        input()\n"
"`);\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/streams.md:83
msgid ""
"Note that the `input()` function automatically reads a line of text and "
"removes the trailing newline. If we use `sys.stdin.read` we see that "
"newlines have been appended to strings that don't end in a newline:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/streams.md:87
msgid ""
"pyodide.setStdin(\n"
"  new StdinHandler([\"a\", \"bcd\\n\", \"efg\", undefined, \"h\", \"i\"]),\n"
");\n"
"pyodide.runPython(String.raw`\n"
"    import sys\n"
"    assert sys.stdin.read() == \"a\\nbcd\\nefg\\n\"\n"
"    assert sys.stdin.read() == \"h\\ni\\n\"\n"
"`);\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/streams.md:98
msgid "Instead of strings we can return the list of utf8 bytes for the input:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/streams.md:100
msgid ""
"pyodide.setStdin(\n"
"  new StdinHandler(\n"
"    [0x61 /* a */, 0x0a /* \\n */, 0x62 /* b */, 0x63 /* c */],\n"
"    true,\n"
"  ),\n"
");\n"
"pyodide.runPython(`\n"
"    assert input() == \"a\"\n"
"    assert input() == \"bc\"\n"
"`);\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/streams.md:113
msgid ""
"Or we can return a `Uint8Array` with the utf8-encoded text that we wish to "
"render:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/streams.md:116
msgid ""
"pyodide.setStdin(\n"
"  new StdinHandler([new Uint8Array([0x61, 0x0a, 0x62, 0x63])]),\n"
");\n"
"pyodide.runPython(`\n"
"    assert input() == \"a\"\n"
"    assert input() == \"bc\"\n"
"`);\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/streams.md:126
msgid "A read handler"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/streams.md:128
msgid ""
"A read handler takes a `Uint8Array` as an argument and is supposed to place "
"the data into this buffer and return the number of bytes read. This is "
"useful in Node. For example, the following class can be used to read from a "
"Node file descriptor:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/streams.md:133
msgid ""
"const fs = require(\"fs\");\n"
"const tty = require(\"tty\");\n"
"class NodeReader {\n"
"  constructor(fd) {\n"
"    this.fd = fd;\n"
"    this.isatty = tty.isatty(fd);\n"
"  }\n"
"\n"
"  read(buffer) {\n"
"    return fs.readSync(this.fd, buffer);\n"
"  }\n"
"}\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/streams.md:148
msgid ""
"For instance to set stdin to read from a file called `input.txt`, we can do "
"the following:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/streams.md:151
msgid ""
"const fd = fs.openSync(\"input.txt\", \"r\");\n"
"py.setStdin(new NodeReader(fd));\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/streams.md:156
msgid "Or we can read from node's stdin (the default behavior) as follows:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/streams.md:158
msgid ""
"fd = fs.openSync(\"/dev/stdin\", \"r\");\n"
"py.setStdin(new NodeReader(fd));\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/streams.md:163 ../../../usage/streams.md:353
msgid "isatty"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/streams.md:165
msgid ""
"It is possible to control whether or not {py:meth}`sys.stdin.isatty() <io."
"IOBase.isatty>` returns true with the `isatty` option:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/streams.md:168
msgid ""
"pyodide.setStdin(new StdinHandler([], {isatty: true}));\n"
"pyodide.runPython(`\n"
"    import sys\n"
"    assert sys.stdin.isatty() # returns true as we requested\n"
"`);\n"
"pyodide.setStdin(new StdinHandler([], {isatty: false}));\n"
"pyodide.runPython(`\n"
"  assert not sys.stdin.isatty() # returns false as we requested\n"
"`);\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/streams.md:180
msgid ""
"This will change the behavior of cli applications that behave differently in "
"an interactive terminal, for example pytest does this."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/streams.md:183
msgid "Raising IO errors"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/streams.md:185
msgid ""
"To raise an IO error in either a `stdin` or `read` handler, you should throw "
"an IO error as follows:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/streams.md:188
msgid "throw new pyodide.FS.ErrnoError(pyodide.ERRNO_CODES.EIO);\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/streams.md:192
msgid "for instance, saying:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/streams.md:194
msgid ""
"pyodide.setStdin({\n"
"  read(buf) {\n"
"    throw new pyodide.FS.ErrnoError(pyodide.ERRNO_CODES.EIO);\n"
"  },\n"
"});\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/streams.md:202
msgid "is the same as `pyodide.setStdin({error: true})`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/streams.md:204
msgid "Handling Keyboard interrupts"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/streams.md:206
msgid ""
"To handle a keyboard interrupt in an input handler, you should periodically "
"call {js:func}`pyodide.checkInterrupt`. For example, the following stdin "
"handler always raises a keyboard interrupt:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/streams.md:210
msgid ""
"const interruptBuffer = new Int32Array(new SharedArrayBuffer(4));\n"
"pyodide.setInterruptBuffer(interruptBuffer);\n"
"pyodide.setStdin({\n"
"  read(buf) {\n"
"    // Put signal into interrupt buffer\n"
"    interruptBuffer[0] = 2;\n"
"    // Call checkInterrupt to raise an error\n"
"    pyodide.checkInterrupt();\n"
"    console.log(\n"
"      \"This code won't ever be executed because pyodide.checkInterrupt "
"raises an error!\",\n"
"    );\n"
"  },\n"
"});\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/streams.md:226
msgid ""
"For a more realistic example that handles reading stdin in a worker and also "
"keyboard interrupts, you might something like the following code:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/streams.md:229
msgid ""
"pyodide.setStdin({read(buf) {\n"
"  const timeoutMilliseconds = 100;\n"
"  while(true) {\n"
"    switch(Atomics.wait(stdinSharedBuffer, 0, 0, timeoutMilliseconds) {\n"
"      case \"timed-out\":\n"
"        // 100 ms passed but got no data, check for keyboard interrupt then "
"return to waiting on data.\n"
"        pyodide.checkInterrupt();\n"
"        break;\n"
"      case \"ok\":\n"
"        // ... handle the data somehow\n"
"        break;\n"
"    }\n"
"  }\n"
"}});\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/streams.md:246
msgid "See also {ref}`interrupting_execution`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/streams.md:248
msgid "Standard Out / Standard Error"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/streams.md:252
msgid ""
"{js:func}`pyodide.setStdout` and {js:func}`pyodide.setStderr` respectively "
"set the standard output and standard error handlers. These APIs are "
"identical except in their defaults, so we will only discuss the `pyodide."
"setStdout` except in cases where they differ."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/streams.md:257
msgid ""
"As with {js:func}`pyodide.setStdin`, there are quite a few different ways to "
"set the standard output handlers."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/streams.md:262
msgid ""
"As with stdin, `pyodide.setStdout()` sets the default behavior. In node, "
"this is to write directly to `process.stdout`. In the browser, the default "
"is as if you wrote `setStdout({batched: (str) => console.log(str)})` see "
"below."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/streams.md:268
msgid "A batched handler"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/streams.md:270
msgid ""
"A batched handler is the easiest standard out handler to implement but it is "
"also the coarsest. It is intended to use with APIs like `console.log` that "
"don't understand partial lines of text or for quick and dirty code."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/streams.md:274
msgid "The batched handler receives a string which is either:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/streams.md:276
msgid "a complete line of text with the newline removed or"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/streams.md:277
msgid "a partial line of text that was flushed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/streams.md:279
msgid "For instance after:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/streams.md:281
msgid ""
"print(\"hello!\")\n"
"import sys\n"
"print(\"partial line\", end=\"\")\n"
"sys.stdout.flush()\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/streams.md:288
msgid ""
"the batched handler is called with `\"hello!\"` and then with `\"partial "
"line\"`. Note that there is no indication that `\"hello!\"` was a complete "
"line of text and `\"partial line\"` was not."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/streams.md:292
msgid "A raw handler"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/streams.md:294
msgid ""
"A raw handler receives the output one character code at a time. This is "
"neither very convenient nor very efficient. It is present primarily for "
"backwards compatibility reasons."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/streams.md:298
msgid "For example, the following code:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/streams.md:300
msgid ""
"print(\"h\")\n"
"import sys\n"
"print(\"p \", end=\"\")\n"
"print(\"l\", end=\"\")\n"
"sys.stdout.flush()\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/streams.md:308
msgid "will call the raw handler with the sequence of bytes:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/streams.md:310
msgid ""
"0x68 - h\n"
"0x0A - newline\n"
"0x70 - p\n"
"0x20 - space\n"
"0x6c - l\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/streams.md:318
msgid "A write handler"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/streams.md:320
msgid ""
"A write handler takes a `Uint8Array` as an argument and is supposed to write "
"the data in this buffer to standard output and return the number of bytes "
"written. For example, the following class can be used to write to a Node "
"file descriptor:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/streams.md:324
msgid ""
"const fs = require(\"fs\");\n"
"const tty = require(\"tty\");\n"
"class NodeWriter {\n"
"  constructor(fd) {\n"
"    this.fd = fd;\n"
"    this.isatty = tty.isatty(fd);\n"
"  }\n"
"\n"
"  write(buffer) {\n"
"    return fs.writeSync(this.fd, buffer);\n"
"  }\n"
"}\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/streams.md:339
msgid "Using it as follows redirects output from Pyodide to `out.txt`:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/streams.md:341
msgid ""
"const fd = fs.openSync(\"out.txt\", \"w\");\n"
"py.setStdout(new NodeWriter(fd));\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/streams.md:346
msgid "Or the following gives the default behavior:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/streams.md:348
msgid ""
"const fd = fs.openSync(\"out.txt\", \"w\");\n"
"py.setStdout(new NodeWriter(process.stdout.fd));\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/streams.md:355
msgid ""
"As with `stdin`, is possible to control whether or not {py:meth}`sys.stdout."
"isatty() <io.IOBase.isatty>` returns true with the `isatty` option. You "
"cannot combine `isatty: true` with a batched handler."
msgstr ""
